-- Japan Stocks Fall as Foodmakers, Developers Lead Losses
-- B y   Y o s h i a k i   N o h a r a   a n d   M a s a a k i   I w a m o t o
-- 2013-11-06T00:06:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-06/japan-stocks-fall-as-foodmakers-developers-lead-losses.html
Japanese  stocks  fell, with the Topix
index poised for a fourth day of losses, as food and real-estate
companies led declines.  The Topix slipped 0.1 percent to 1,181.24 as of 9:03 a.m.
in Tokyo. About four shares dropped for every three that rose on
the 1,746-member gauge. The Nikkei 225 Stock Average lost 0.4
percent to 14,167.95.  “As earnings season hits the home stretch, results have
been somewhat lacking in impact,” said  Toshihiko Matsuno , a
strategist at Tokyo-based SMBC Friend Securities Co. “We
haven’t seen as many upward forecast revisions as expected.”  The Topix trailed 23 other developed markets tracked by
Bloomberg in October, rising less than 0.1 percent. The measure
remains the best performer this year as of yesterday in the
group with a 38 percent rally. Shares rose as unprecedented
monetary easing by the  Bank of Japan  weakened the yen, improving
the earnings outlook for exporters.  More than 500 companies on the 1,746-member Topix announce
results  this week , according to data compiled by Bloomberg.
Toyota Motor Corp., the world’s largest automaker, is among
those posting earnings today at the close. Of the 190 companies
that have announced results this quarter and for which Bloomberg
had estimates, 58 percent topped expectations.  Earnings per share on the gauge are expected to increase 44
percent from the previous quarter, according to analyst
 projections  compiled by Bloomberg.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. The equity measure fell 0.3 percent yesterday, as
investors awaited data to gauge the health of the  U.S. economy .  Faster-estimated expansion in a U.S. services gauge in
October stoked speculation the economy is strong enough for the
 Federal Reserve  to cut stimulus earlier than anticipated. The
country issues economic growth and employment data starting
tomorrow.  U.S. Data  The Fed last week said it needs to see more evidence of
sustained improvement before slowing the pace of its $85 billion
monthly bond purchases. Economists in a Bloomberg survey project
that tapering will begin in March.  The Topix traded at 1.22 times book value yesterday,
compared to 2.55 for the S&P 500 and 1.80 for the Stoxx Europe
600 Index. The Topix’s 30-day  historic volatility  was at 16.33
yesterday, down from its five-year median of 19.18.  To contact the reporters on this story:
